## Crossing latitude = 0

The other day, I was crossing the equator into the southern hemisphere.  The equator is where latitude is zero.  Crossing the equator is a non-event in this part of the world, much like how crossing the prime meridian (where longitude is zero) is a non event in England.  But my being a little giddy, I wanted to see the latitude on my phone screen change from a small `N` to a small `S` for the first time.   I had never before stared so intently at a screen.  @fig-eqlatlon shows my latitude to be 0.000 035 727 in the immediate second before the `N` changed to `S`.

![Latitude and longitude coordinates on crossing the equator.](image_01.png){#fig-eqlatlon fig-align="left" width=40%}

After the initial excitment subsided, the nine decimal places bothered me --- even more so, because the apparent accuracy is $\pm{}$ 5.8 m.  There are not many instruments out there in science and engineering that can measure to nine decimal places.  So, it got me thinking: what level of precision do nine decimal places signify?

## A little background

I have been tracking the realtime position of my backpacking trip across Asia.  The screenshot in @fig-eqlatlon is from the Android app [GPS Logger](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=eu.basicairdata.graziano.gpslogger&hl=en_US), which I have been using for a long time.  I have never bothered to pay too much attention to the numbers on the screen ... until now.  Nine decimal places!

### GNSS

GNSS stands for *global navigation satellite system*.  [GPS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Positioning_System) is the American version of GNSS.  The others are

* Russia's [GLONASS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GLONASS);
* China's [BeiDou](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BeiDou_Navigation_Satellite_System);
* Europe's [Galileo](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galileo_(satellite_navigation)).

Most people don't care about the distinction; they just call it all GPS, a bit like how all vacuum cleaners are called hoovers.

### GNSS signal structure

GNSS satellites continuously bombard the Earth with three things in their in their signal.

1. The satellite's date and time.
2. The ephemeris, which contains precise orbital information for that particular satellite.  Takes 30 seconds to transmit from the satellite and is valid for four hours.
3. The almanac, which contains low-resolution orbital information for *all* the satellites in the constellation.  Takes 12.5 minutes to transmit from the satellite and is valid for upto two weeks.

Ephemeris data from at least three satellites is needed before you can get a 2D fix on your position. This is then displayed on your device as longitude and latitude, like @fig-eqlatlon.

## Deciphering the numbers

Back when the French were writing the manual for Isis, offing people of their heads, they took the opportunity to tidy up the quagmire of units that existed at the time.  A little known fact is the role unscrupulous merchants played in ripping off the ordinary man in everyday transactions, using dodgy scales and units, outraging people to the point of revolution.

Once the bloodthirst was satiated, they defined the metre as a length which, when multiplied by 10 million, takes you from the equator to a pole.  In other words, if you walk in a straight line from the equator to the North Pole, you will by definition have covered 10 000 000 metres.[^1]

[^1]: The definition of the metre was changed in 2019 to the distance light travels in a vacuum in $\frac{1}{\textrm{299 792 458}}$ of a second.  However, that does not really change anything insofar as this article is concerned.

Starting at the centre of the Earth, if you drew a line segment to the North Pole and another to the equator, the angle that subtends the two lines is exactly 90°.



::: {.cell layout-align="left"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![The angle between the North Pole and the equator is 90°.](gps_files/figure-html/fig-arc-1.png){#fig-arc fig-align='left' width=384}
:::
:::



Knowing this, we can do a quick calculation that tells us how much distance is covered by each degree.

$$
\frac{10 \, 000 \, 000 \, \mathrm{m}}{90°} = 111 \, 111 \, \textrm{m per degree}
$$

One degree of latitude, therefore, covers 111 111 m (111 km).  That is the precision at zero decimal places.  Each decimal place adds an order of magnitude of precision, such that

$$
\frac{\textrm{111 111}}{10^{x}} = y
$$

where $x$ is the number of decimal places and $y$ the precision.



