At nine decimals (@fig-eqlatlon), I should be pinned down to

$$
\frac{\textrm{111 111}}{10^9} = \textrm{0.000 111 111 m}
$$

which is 0.1 mm --- about the width of a strand of hair.

Clearly, something is not right.  Either the nine-decimal precision is wrong, or the $\pm{}$ 5.8 m accuracy figure is wrong, because my position cannot be known to the width of a hair and still be out by 5.8 m.

The accuracy value ($\pm{}$ 5.8 m) suggests my device is computing at somewhere between four and five decimal places.  That means the additional decimals are bogus: they are artifacts of the computation process that were not discarded.

The more you know.
